"1532","about 1577":"about 1577","1608":"1608","1529":"1529","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Wilcott, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Deddington, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Deddington, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Sandridge, Hertfordshire, England":"Sandridge, Hertfordshire, England","Hemel Hempstead, , Hertfordshire, England":"Hemel Hempstead, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Deddington, Oxfordshire, England":"Deddington, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kinkey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Swiss German <b>Dünki</b>, unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sharley","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name from any of the various places (in the West Midlands, Derbyshire, Hampshire, and Surrey) named in Old English from <i>scīr</i> ‘county, shire’ or <i>scīr</i> ‘bright’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’. It was given by  Charlotte Brontë  to the heroine of her novel Shirley (  1849 ). According to the novel, her parents had selected the name in prospect of a male child and used it regardless. <i>Shirley</i> had earlier been used as a boy's name (  Charlotte Brontë  refers to it as a ‘masculine cognomen’), but this literary influence fixed it firmly as a girl's name. It was strongly reinforced during the 1930s and 40s by the popularity of the child film star  Shirley Temple  (  b. 1928 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":45,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":54,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":65,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":67,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sharley Kinkey was born in 1504, in Sandridge, Hertfordshire, England, her father, Robert Kinkey, was 21 and her mother, Joane South, was 21. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Sir Newell Edgar Pope. She died in 1577, in Deddington, Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1504–1577":"1504–1577","1504–1588":"1504–1588","1529–1593":"1529–1593","1532–1590":"1532–1590","1538–1608":"1538–1608","1484–1549":"1484–1549","1484–1577":"1484–1577","1484":"1484","1571":"1571","1593":"1593","1590":"1590","before 1504":"enne 1504","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","about 1549":"umbes 1549","1577":"1577","1588":"1588","1532":"1532","about 1577":"umbes 1577","1608":"1608","1529":"1529","1538":"1538","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Wilcott, Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",